    <header>
        <h1>MNEMET Research Units</h1>
        <p>MNEMET aims to bring together researchers from three Italian universities.</p>
    </header>

    <section>
        <h2>University of Trieste</h2>

        <article>
            <h3>Prof. Roberta Pappad√†</h3>
            <p>
                Associate professor of Statistics and Principal Investigator of MNEMET. 
                Her research interests include Copula-based modelling, Computational Statistics, 
                Classification and clustering, Time series clustering, Machine learning algorithms, 
                Discrimination detection, and Ensemble methods in unsupervised problems. 
                She has published in <em>Statistics and Computing</em>, <em>Spatial Statistics</em>, 
                <em>Fuzzy Sets and Systems</em>.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article>
            <h3>Prof. Gaetano Carmeci</h3>
            <p>
                Associate professor of Econometrics. Research interests: Bayesian and spatial econometrics, 
                panel cointegration, forecasting of electricity prices. Published in the <em>Journal of Macroeconomics</em>, 
                <em>Journal of Risk and Insurance</em>, <em>Journal of Policy Modeling</em>, and 
                <em>Journal of Public Economic Theory</em>.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article>
            <h3>Prof. Giovanni Millo</h3>
            <p>
                Associate professor of Economic Statistics, formerly at Assicurazioni Generali. 
                His interests are Panel Data Econometrics, Spatial Econometrics, Computational Econometrics, and Insurance Economics. 
                Published in <em>Journal of Applied Econometrics</em>, <em>Journal of Statistical Software</em>, 
                <em>Journal of Spatial Econometrics</em>, and <em>Journal of Risk and Insurance</em>.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article>
            <h3>Dr. Vincenzo Gioia</h3>
            <p>
                Post-doctoral researcher in the Department of Economics, Business, Mathematics, and Statistics. 
                Ph.D. in Managerial and Actuarial Sciences. Research areas: semi-parametric regression, statistical computing, 
                open-source software, with applications in engineering, environmental statistics, and life sciences.
            </p>
        </article>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>University of Milan</h2>

        <article>
            <h3>Prof. Luca Rossini</h3>
            <p>
                Associate professor of Statistics and Senior Researcher at Fondazione Eni Enrico Mattei. 
                Co-PI and head of the local unit. His research spans Bayesian inference, time series analysis, 
                energy economics, and nonlinear models. Published in <em>Journal of Business and Economic Statistics</em>, 
                <em>Journal of Econometrics</em>, <em>International Journal of Forecasting</em>, and 
                <em>Annals of Applied Statistics</em>.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article>
            <h3>Prof. Andrea Bastianin</h3>
            <p>
                Associate professor of Economic Policy and Program Director at Fondazione Eni Enrico Mattei. 
                Research interests: Time Series Econometrics, Environmental and Energy Economics, Forecasting, and Critical raw materials. 
                Publications in <em>Energy Economics</em>, <em>Macroeconomic Dynamics</em>, <em>Energy Policy</em>, 
                and <em>Economic Modelling</em>.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article>
            <h3>Andrea Viselli</h3>
            <p>
                Post-doctoral researcher in Econometrics. Focuses on time series models, nowcasting, and forecasting evaluation. 
                Currently completing a Ph.D. at the University of Milan and Pavia under Prof. Fabrizio Iacone and Prof. Luca Rossini.
            </p>
        </article>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Free University of Bozen-Bolzano</h2>

        <article>
            <h3>Prof. F. Marta L. Di Lascio</h3>
            <p>
                Associate professor of Statistics and head of the local unit. 
                Research interests: stochastic models with copulas, clustering techniques for complex data, 
                and methods for high-dimensional spatial, time series, and panel data. 
                Published in <em>Biometrics</em>, <em>Computational Statistics and Data Analysis</em>, 
                <em>Spatial Statistics</em>, <em>Journal of Classification</em>, and 
                <em>Journal of Banking and Finance</em>.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article>
            <h3>Dr. Selene Perazzini</h3>
            <p>
                Researcher in statistics focused on spatio-temporal modelling for environmental risk. 
                Ph.D. from IMT School for Advanced Studies Lucca on georeferenced data, natural risks, and insurance. 
                Currently research assistant at Free University of Bozen-Bolzano, working on multivariate environmental 
                time series with complex dependencies.
            </p>
        </article>
    </section>
